opriate method for answering the question. To support this process students search and review related literature, reading and critiquing sample papers to identify key components of a successful academic paper. The tutorial continues the development of students' scholarly writing skills and research abilities, discussing writing techniques and appropriate sourcing and citation methods as they study each of the elements of a proposal and analyze proposal examples. Students are asked to write and revise each section of the proposal, culminating in a draft of a complete proposal by the end of the tutorial.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePrerequisites: \u003c/strong\u003eStudents must be candidates in the Master of Liberal Arts, Mathematics for Teaching. They should have completed eight courses toward the degree, including successful completion of MATH 15, be in good academic standing, and have the approval of the instructor. Students should submit a two- to three-page document by August 1 to Dr. Engelward with \"Thesis Proposal Tutorial Prerequisites\" in the subject line of the e-mail. The document should include a potential thesis topic, a list of research questions, some background information about the research topic (including three references), and the rationale for the proposed research (why the questions are worth asking).  Please get in touch with Dr. Engelward with any questions you might have about getting this document in on time for the fall tutorial.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSchedule/Assignments\u003c/strong\u003e:  This tutorial course is different from other courses you might have taken in the sense that it is set up as an individualized process in which the pace of your progress will follow your own motivation and speed.  Although there are no specific due dates for each of the items described below, there are still some rough guidelines given that you should be aware of for you to be able to finish a completed proposal draft by the end of the semester.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFirst Phase - September through early/mid-October\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e \u003cstrong\u003eProposal prework: \u003c/strong\u003eDuring the beginning of the semester (first four to five weeks) you will be asked to view a series of short video modules along with completing a number of brief assignments to make sure you’ve understood the material covered for each topic.  These modules will include:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eUsing Harvard library resources\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eUsing the Guide to the Thesis website\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSelecting an appropriate thesis topic/research questions\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eOverview of sections of a thesis proposal\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTips for academic writing\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eProper note taking procedures\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWorking with Harvard’s IRB\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWhat you can do with your thesis after it’s done\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAfter working through these introductory modules in the first part of the semester, there are a number of key steps in the preparation of a successful thesis proposal itself listed out below.  Note that these stages aren’t necessarily sequential – and you will be working on the first three at the same time as going through the video modules listed above.  Stages four and five might overlap as you continue your library research and refine your thesis project goals.  It might also be the case that you refocus your project and need to loop back to an earlier stage. \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eProposal preparation:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStage One:\u003c/strong\u003e  Development of general thesis topic idea.  You will have started this search already with your tutorial prerequisites document.  During the CTP tutorial we will work on focusing in on a specific area of research for your thesis project.   \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStage Two:\u003c/strong\u003e Continue to read broadly about your topic area by consulting Harvard’s library resources (on campus or online, meeting with research librarians, etc.)  While you are doing this you might run into articles that are tangentially related to your original topic, but that help you redefine your topic, or perhaps lead to a modification of your topic.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStage Three:\u003c/strong\u003e Narrow your topic to a focused and confined issue for your thesis project.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSecond Phase - October:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStage Four:\u003c/strong\u003e Generate a substantive set of scholarly resources for your topic (i.e. a comprehensive bibliography).  As part of the CTP tutorial, we will discuss what is considered appropriate from an academic/scholarly perspective (e.g. as useful as it can be at times, you shouldn’t include Wikipedia in your thesis’s final references list). \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStage Five:\u003c/strong\u003e As you are reading and developing your bibliography, you should work on generating a list of potential thesis questions to answer along with hypotheses.  This is key, as a thesis is not simply a summary of information that you have read about a subject – there needs to be a point to your thesis, and to make this happen you need to construct an argument that represents an original contribution to scholarship or provides a novel perspective about your topic.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThird Phase - November through December:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStage Six:\u003c/strong\u003e Create a draft thesis proposal document.  To do this, we will break apart the various sections of the thesis proposal (e.g. background of thesis project, thesis project description, work plan, reference list, etc.) so that you will work through the various sections one by one, until you have put together a complete working draft of your thesis proposal. \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eHaving completed Stage Six, you will have successfully completed the main work for the CTP tutorial.  However, there is a final stage of the proposal process which is critical to making the transition to working with a thesis director and starting the actual thesis project:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBy end of tutorial, or within several months after tutorial has ended:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFinal Stage:\u003c/strong\u003e  Produce several drafts of your proposal incorporating all of the feedback provided about your proposal during the tutorial.  Typically, it take three to four drafts before approval for your proposal can be given.   \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003cem\u003eThere are three main reasons for polishing your thesis proposal:\u003c/em\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFirst\u003c/strong\u003e, it gives you critical practice in the process of scholarly writing that will carry over into your thesis project as you begin to write the actual thesis.  We want thesis directors to concentrate on the content of your thesis work, and we do not expect them to have to do any basic copy editing for your writing.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSecond\u003c/strong\u003e, your thesis proposal provides a work plan for your thesis project.  The more detail you put into the proposal in terms of steps, timing, specification of deliverables, etc., the easier it will be for you to follow through on doing the actual thesis work.  Consider the proposal a blueprint for a house you will be building.  The more you plan at this stage, the simpler it will be to build and the less likely you will be to run into issues later on (proper planning prevents problems!)\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFinally\u003c/strong\u003e, your Research Advisor will share your completed proposal with potential thesis directors.  The more effort you put into producing a well-crafted proposal, showing your serious intentions as a student, the more likely your RA will be able to locate a thesis director who will be able to help you with your thesis project.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTutorial Expectations\u003c/strong\u003e:  The tutorial, when taken for non-credit, is not a graded course (those taking it for graduate credit will be assigned a grade).  Given that the main goal for the tutorial is to provide support in creating a strong, viable thesis proposal, then the main expectation for those registered for the tutorial is to make diligent effort during the semester towards this goal, with the primary deliverable being a completed thesis proposal draft by the end of the semester.   \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTexts\u003c/strong\u003e: The only required text for the proposal tutorial is the APA’s publication manual (sixth edition – available relatively inexpensively online or at the Harvard Coop). Other readings, including articles on conducting research and scholarly writing, will be provided during the tutorial. \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn addition to this text, you should also refer to the following two websites:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e1) Guide to the ALM Thesis: \u003ca href=\"https://thesis.extension.harvard.edu\"\u003ehttps://thesis.extension.harvard.edu\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e2) Information about the overall thesis process on the main Extension School website: \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e \u003ca href=\"www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/completing-your-degree/thesis-process\"\u003ewww.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/completing-your-degree/thesis-process\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e \u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAcademic Integrity:\u003c/strong\u003e  Please note that as a Harvard Extension School student, you are responsible for reading and understanding the Extension School's policies on academic integrity and how to use sources responsibly. \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/student-conduct/academic-integrity\"\u003ewww.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/student-conduct/academic-integrity\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDisability Services: \u003c/strong\u003eThe Extension School is committed to providing an accessible academic community. The Accessibility Services Office offers a variety of accommodations and services to students who might need them. Please visit \u003ca href=\"www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/resources/accessibility-student-services\"\u003ewww.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/resources/accessibility-student-services\u003c/a\u003e for more information, and please feel free to contact the office at Accessibility@dcemail.harvard.edu or 617-998-9640\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI look forward to meeting and working with you in person or online this fall!\u003c/p\u003e","notices":[]};
